precipitated with alcohol, cleaned, and then conﬁrmed by a spectrophotometer.

DNA sequencing is important and needed in order for the sequencing to go smoothly. When we check the
Purity of the PCR at 260 and 280 nm wavelength we always get 1.8 because it's a fragment that's pure DNA.
Puriﬁcation is important because if there is any contamination present the ampliﬁcation would not occur and
it would disrupt the DNA sequencing procedure.
This is a technique used to distinguish two different types of bacteria based on what constitutes their cell
wall. The two groups are gram negative and gram positive. There are a series of steps in this process: First
the bacteria is put on a slide that is heat ﬁxed so it will stay on the slide, it is stained with the crystal violet
or gram stain for one minute, then iodine is introduced to the bacteria which makes the crystal violet stick to
the cell wall for one minute, then an alcohol is applied to decolorize the cell for three seconds, after a
secondary stain stafrin is put onto the the slide with the bacteria for one minute, then rinse with water
brieﬂy maximum of ﬁve seconds. After examine the slide under a microscope to determine if it is gram
positive or negative.

This determines the order of the nucleotide base pairs in a DNA molecule. This can tell scientists genetic
information about the carrier. This is used commonly when scientists want to ﬁnd out which DNA determines
certain genes, how they will be able to turn off or on a certain gene, or what piece of DNA carries their
regulatory instructions. This used to be a very long and expensive process until the completion of the Human
Genome Project which has made it faster and less expensive.

The method is referring to hydrogen-linked bases that form nucleic acids in DNA and RNA. This method is
known as Watson Crick Base pairing because Dr. Francis Crick and Dr. James Watson because they were the
people that discovered the fact that the DNA has a helical shape.Dr. Francis Crick discovered that the two
strands of the DNA are able to form the helical shape and intertwine with the help of hydrogen bonds. DNA
is composed of four nucleobases adenine (A), thymine (T), guanine (G), and cytosine (C). Purines are adenine
& guanine while pyrimidine bases are cytosine & thymine. Adenine pairs with thymine and cytosine pairs
with guanine.
